1
00:00:10,342 --> 00:00:11,042
Good evening.

2
00:00:11,384 --> 00:00:13,146
I hope you had a fruitful day.

3
00:00:13,166 --> 00:00:16,972
I do not say happy, but I hope it has been a happy day.

4
00:00:18,134 --> 00:00:33,817
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodasa

5
00:00:34,591 --> 00:00:43,040
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa.

6
00:00:43,902 --> 00:00:50,649
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

7
00:00:50,670 --> 00:00:56,076
So these past few days we've been looking at anatta,

8
00:00:56,478 --> 00:01:05,054
as an intellectual exercise, really, just trying to understand it, trying to understand the way the Buddha expresses it in the scriptures.

9
00:01:05,736 --> 00:01:10,984
And hopefully that's become more clear, become more clear to me, trying to teach it, frankly.

10
00:01:12,629 --> 00:01:14,992
But now we have to get down to the practice.

11
00:01:15,378 --> 00:01:22,149
How do we actually investigate this in terms of our vipassana, in terms of our practice?

12
00:01:22,168 --> 00:01:30,402
So many of you who've worked with me, of course, will have heard me speak about it and explain it.

13
00:01:31,203 --> 00:01:34,388
So for you, it's a bit of a revision, you might say.

14
00:01:34,828 --> 00:01:42,381
But for those who haven't, it might offer you a technique, a way of investigating not-self.

15
00:01:47,254 --> 00:01:51,459
Uh, so there's three things, first of all, deconstruction, right?

16
00:01:51,478 --> 00:01:53,299
To deconstruct what we experienced.

17
00:01:53,941 --> 00:02:01,406
The second one is, um, uh, control seeing, seeing that what control we have, what control we don't have.

18
00:02:02,147 --> 00:02:13,276
Uh, remember that was one of the, of the, and that's a lack of, so to the, that second discourse on not self, he starts off by saying, if this body were me, I'd be able to say, don't fall ill, et cetera, et cetera.

19
00:02:13,817 --> 00:02:16,840
And the final, and the third one is objectification.

20
00:02:17,495 --> 00:02:19,657
to turn everything into an object.

21
00:02:19,697 --> 00:02:21,378
If it's an object, it can't be me.

22
00:02:22,379 --> 00:02:29,286
So when we talk about deconstruction, we can take a very simple object.

23
00:02:29,605 --> 00:02:39,415
Everybody suffers from pain in the knee, usually, unless you're a yoga person.

24
00:02:40,257 --> 00:02:44,080
It took me years to be able to sit without any pain in my knees.

25
00:02:45,581 --> 00:02:47,062
So, okay, the pain comes.

26
00:02:47,514 --> 00:02:49,337
It draws your attention.

27
00:02:50,019 --> 00:02:55,167
And the first thing is, of course, your reaction, which is not to want the pain, the desire to move.

28
00:02:56,269 --> 00:02:58,491
So you have to wait for that to die away.

29
00:02:58,913 --> 00:02:59,954
Just recognize it.

30
00:03:00,074 --> 00:03:01,417
Desiring, desiring.

31
00:03:02,959 --> 00:03:03,719
Feel it, of course.

32
00:03:03,780 --> 00:03:05,383
Feel the desire to move.

33
00:03:05,522 --> 00:03:06,844
It's all about feeling.

34
00:03:06,865 --> 00:03:15,057
And then when that's passed and you find yourself equanimous, that's the time to start using the word pain.

35
00:03:16,490 --> 00:03:19,715
Okay, so we're using the word pain or discomfort, whatever.

36
00:03:20,395 --> 00:03:23,700
And of course, we're not trying to get rid of pain or defeat pain, right?

37
00:03:23,741 --> 00:03:25,943
That's a no-no.

38
00:03:25,963 --> 00:03:28,247
And if the pain gets too much, well, you move, right?

39
00:03:28,268 --> 00:03:30,371
Make the intention to move and off you go.

40
00:03:30,991 --> 00:03:32,794
But let's say that the pain is bearable.

41
00:03:33,455 --> 00:03:35,657
So you've got this pain, pain.

42
00:03:36,199 --> 00:03:42,147
And then what you have to do is deconstruct it, by which we mean you go into the pain.

43
00:03:42,788 --> 00:03:45,432
You try and see what it's actually made of.

44
00:03:45,717 --> 00:03:48,000
And when you get in there, you might find heat.

45
00:03:48,620 --> 00:03:50,081
You might find tightness.

46
00:03:50,102 --> 00:03:51,544
You might find pressure.

47
00:03:52,504 --> 00:03:56,649
You might find little bits of sparkly sensations.

48
00:03:56,870 --> 00:03:59,513
All sorts of little things might happen.

49
00:04:00,073 --> 00:04:01,715
And your noting word might change.

50
00:04:01,915 --> 00:04:04,699
So you might be saying tight, heat, et cetera.

51
00:04:05,780 --> 00:04:11,546
And make that very clear to yourself by staying there and feeling it.

52
00:04:11,947 --> 00:04:13,368
It's not an intellectual process.

53
00:04:13,389 --> 00:04:14,610
You don't want to think about it.

54
00:04:15,012 --> 00:04:27,105
It's a direct experience of these sensations, which are the information coming to us, and then the mind does something with it.

55
00:04:28,307 --> 00:04:34,394
Now, at the second level of perception, that's when the word pain comes up.

56
00:04:34,415 --> 00:04:37,478
And that's when you realize that pain is a mental construct.

57
00:04:37,858 --> 00:04:39,279
It doesn't actually exist.

58
00:04:39,461 --> 00:04:41,543
What exists are these sensations.

59
00:04:42,232 --> 00:04:45,156
Now it's not as though you have to forget what pain is.

60
00:04:46,076 --> 00:05:01,577
You need to know when to go to the doctor, but there's that clarity now that pain is basically a concept that we have about certain groups of sensations that arise from the body itself, right?

61
00:05:01,598 --> 00:05:02,939
So that's your sense base.

62
00:05:03,459 --> 00:05:10,769
Remember the retina is for the eye, sensations in the body, your felt, your sensation base.

63
00:05:11,898 --> 00:05:19,526
So by deconstructing something, you're taking away its substance, right?

64
00:05:19,545 --> 00:05:23,089
And by doing that, you're realizing there's actually not much there.

65
00:05:23,490 --> 00:05:32,740
And as you go into it, that sort of detail, the quality of impermanence becomes much more obvious.

66
00:05:33,461 --> 00:05:37,245
So whatever is impermanent, of course, can't be substantial.

67
00:05:37,286 --> 00:05:38,086
It can't be a self.

68
00:05:38,127 --> 00:05:39,507
It can't be anything because

69
00:05:39,826 --> 00:05:42,369
As soon as it arises, it's virtually disappeared.

70
00:05:44,211 --> 00:06:06,694
So by moving between those two perceptions, the perception of sensations, basic sensations coming in, heat, pressure, etc., and the concept of pain, we're also beginning to see how the mind builds up the world that we are living in.

71
00:06:07,213 --> 00:06:10,740
So remember, we're encased in this little bubble of consciousness.

72
00:06:10,800 --> 00:06:11,841
This is our world.

73
00:06:12,482 --> 00:06:17,630
And whenever in the scriptures the Buddha says, the end of the world, he doesn't mean the end of the cosmos.

74
00:06:17,651 --> 00:06:21,617
He means the end of the world that we constantly are creating.

75
00:06:22,699 --> 00:06:26,444
So that's one way in which we can take away substance from things.

76
00:06:27,346 --> 00:06:29,290
And you can do the same with an emotion.

77
00:06:29,911 --> 00:06:34,538
So if you're isolating now and you're stuck in a room

78
00:06:35,040 --> 00:06:43,050
Uh, et cetera, then I'd say sometime in the evening, especially, uh, you might feel lonely, might feel sad, et cetera.

79
00:06:43,531 --> 00:06:47,576
So if that sort of negative state comes up, you see, you don't think about it.

80
00:06:47,817 --> 00:06:49,939
You don't start indulging this business.

81
00:06:49,959 --> 00:06:52,863
If I'm I'm unlovable, you know, nobody loves me.

82
00:06:52,983 --> 00:06:53,644
Everybody hates me.

83
00:06:54,446 --> 00:06:54,565
Wow.

84
00:06:54,605 --> 00:06:54,805
Is it?

85
00:06:54,826 --> 00:07:00,372
I've got no friends, but you go into the field, the field of loneliness.

86
00:07:00,910 --> 00:07:13,749
And as you take it apart, as you begin to look at it just as sensation, it begins to lose that reality that we give it when we turn it into an emotion.

87
00:07:14,170 --> 00:07:19,497
And, of course, it's at that point that we flip into this, I am lonely.

88
00:07:19,658 --> 00:07:22,281
So there's the identity, right?

89
00:07:22,302 --> 00:07:25,466
When it comes to the pain is I have a bad knee.

90
00:07:25,786 --> 00:07:26,848
There's your possession.

91
00:07:28,009 --> 00:07:30,394
So we're sort of breaking up.

92
00:07:30,661 --> 00:07:44,392
that mental process and recognizing that the I is in a sense, the last step in the process, the sense of identity is the last thing that happens, uh, in that process of perception.

93
00:07:46,134 --> 00:07:46,394
Yeah.

94
00:07:47,716 --> 00:07:55,584
Um, I mean, the one, the one, uh, the one example I use, which I know some of you know, is about ice cream, you see.

95
00:07:55,644 --> 00:08:00,447
So, uh, as soon as you see ice cream, uh, then of course, uh,

96
00:08:00,596 --> 00:08:01,850
There's the memory of it.

97
00:08:02,487 --> 00:08:07,451
And there's the, there's that sense of like, so that's the Veda like it.

98
00:08:08,372 --> 00:08:14,579
So seeing it, it has to go through that process of recognizing it as ice cream.

99
00:08:14,959 --> 00:08:16,380
And then there's the liking of it.

100
00:08:16,680 --> 00:08:18,322
Then there's the one of it.

101
00:08:18,543 --> 00:08:26,591
And then there's the, I want, and as soon as the I comes in, it's very difficult to stop the empowerment and that's the getting right.

102
00:08:26,971 --> 00:08:32,476
So even though I say I like, want, get ice cream, actually.

103
00:08:32,726 --> 00:08:40,595
psychologically, in Buddhist understanding, it's like, want, I, get, I scream.

104
00:08:40,634 --> 00:08:41,456
That's the process.

105
00:08:42,096 --> 00:08:47,481
And it's breaking that up that you realize that this identity is necessary, right?

106
00:08:47,501 --> 00:08:50,926
It's just something we put into that process.

107
00:08:52,687 --> 00:08:55,931
Okay, so you can always do this.

108
00:08:55,990 --> 00:08:57,673
You can start your meditation with this.

109
00:08:57,812 --> 00:09:00,456
If you find the mind's wandering, you can raise the interest.

110
00:09:00,924 --> 00:09:04,269
and, and, and go through that sort of little exercise.

111
00:09:04,509 --> 00:09:06,572
Yeah.

112
00:09:06,592 --> 00:09:17,528
Uh, and now the second thing is, um, this business of, uh, uh, powerlessness or abs, you know, that we haven't got entire control of the body.

113
00:09:18,009 --> 00:09:21,554
So obviously pain in the knees is, is a case in point.

114
00:09:21,695 --> 00:09:28,364
You recognize that the pain has arisen, whether you want it to or not, it's not under your control is the control center is elsewhere.

115
00:09:28,384 --> 00:09:29,466
It's in the body somewhere.

116
00:09:29,485 --> 00:09:30,206
It's in the brain.

117
00:09:30,524 --> 00:09:31,264
whatever you wish.

118
00:09:32,586 --> 00:09:40,557
And it's that disconnection with something that's happening that is disconnecting the I, right?

119
00:09:40,576 --> 00:09:42,139
So it's not all mine.

120
00:09:42,200 --> 00:09:43,081
It's not my pain.

121
00:09:43,140 --> 00:09:44,523
It's just the pain.

122
00:09:45,423 --> 00:09:50,630
And when you have something like loneliness or happiness, then it's not me and I who are happy.

123
00:09:50,910 --> 00:09:53,875
There is an emotion of happiness.

124
00:09:53,894 --> 00:09:56,479
Now, in your noting, you can make that plain to yourself.

125
00:09:56,918 --> 00:09:58,100
There is pain.

126
00:09:58,620 --> 00:09:59,962
There is happiness.

127
00:10:00,403 --> 00:10:01,585
There is sadness.

128
00:10:02,265 --> 00:10:12,419
And just by objectifying it like that, you're undermining that sense of possession and an identity.

129
00:10:14,322 --> 00:10:25,977
And when you step back into that position of the observer, the feeler, you can ask yourself, you know, can the perceiver be the perceived?

130
00:10:26,971 --> 00:10:50,008
and the perceiver be the perceived okay now that takes us on to the uh the third point which is about um um no control well that that that part is about no control it takes us to the third point which is objectify the objectivization of our experience so uh

131
00:10:50,292 --> 00:10:54,717
The two examples I use is first of all, when we were babies, we were all babies.

132
00:10:55,559 --> 00:10:57,783
And the second one is the myth of narcissus.

133
00:10:58,923 --> 00:11:12,163
So seemingly, uh, when we're born and presumably, uh, in the later stages in the womb, uh, for the first four months of our birth, um, everything we experienced is just a, it's just a shower.

134
00:11:12,464 --> 00:11:18,072
It's just a continual bombardment of, of sensations out of which we can, we can make no sense.

135
00:11:18,506 --> 00:11:40,919
there's light coming in there's sounds coming in there's sensations in the body there's smells there's tastes and and it's all one it's not differentiated at all that's what seems to happen uh but of one thing we're very sure uh whether something is pleasant or unpleasant and when we are when we're hungry we definitely tell our mothers we're hungry so

136
00:11:41,153 --> 00:11:47,038
That undifferentiated catastrophe, you can say, of sensation for this poor little baby.

137
00:11:47,438 --> 00:11:50,480
No wonder it sleeps for, what, 16, 18 hours a day or something.

138
00:11:52,062 --> 00:11:56,086
Out of that, there looms, you might say, the first object.

139
00:11:56,147 --> 00:11:59,570
This is what psychologists tell you.

140
00:12:00,049 --> 00:12:03,813
And that object is usually your carer, your mother, usually.

141
00:12:04,474 --> 00:12:08,798
And very slowly over time, this differentiation occurs.

142
00:12:09,065 --> 00:12:11,808
helps to push the outer world outwards.

143
00:12:12,610 --> 00:12:23,604
And so the baby becomes to recognize that there's an outer world, although it might not be so much aware of the inner world, but it's definitely objectifying the outer world.

144
00:12:24,605 --> 00:12:32,336
And then there's also the attachment to the carer, to your mother.

145
00:12:33,136 --> 00:12:37,182
And so it seems that this business of sort of detaching

146
00:12:37,785 --> 00:12:52,240
pulling out in this too close a relationship with our parent begins to sort of break apart.

147
00:12:52,740 --> 00:12:55,124
And there's all this terrible twos and all that.

148
00:12:55,524 --> 00:12:58,827
But by the age of three, we seem to be very clear.

149
00:12:59,427 --> 00:13:01,269
I'm me and everything else is not me.

150
00:13:03,091 --> 00:13:04,192
And that's taken three years.

151
00:13:04,352 --> 00:13:06,054
That's taken three years to push

152
00:13:06,304 --> 00:13:13,313
the outer world out into an object, into something that exists outside me, as different from me.

153
00:13:14,895 --> 00:13:19,261
Now, if you think about it, that's all that's happening in our vipassana.

154
00:13:19,402 --> 00:13:27,071
We are taking a position within ourselves and pushing the inner world outwardly to observe it.

155
00:13:28,894 --> 00:13:33,779
And in so doing, we're sort of reestablishing our identity.

156
00:13:34,418 --> 00:13:43,688
So sometimes we identify with the body, especially if it's a sort of sharp pain like biting your tongue or when you're hungry or whatever.

157
00:13:45,110 --> 00:13:47,634
It's easier for us to identify with our emotions.

158
00:13:47,953 --> 00:13:48,774
I am sad.

159
00:13:49,395 --> 00:13:51,859
And then you pull yourself out of that identity.

160
00:13:52,318 --> 00:13:54,402
It's even easier to get lost in thought.

161
00:13:55,482 --> 00:13:56,663
You don't say I am thinking.

162
00:13:56,683 --> 00:13:57,625
You are thinking.

163
00:13:57,806 --> 00:13:58,907
You are the thinker.

164
00:13:59,511 --> 00:14:12,619
And you pull yourself out of that, out of the imaginative thinking, and you find yourself in this very strange position of being the inner observer, the inner feeler, the one who knows, the experiencer.

165
00:14:13,461 --> 00:14:20,034
And when we've really got that position, everything is manifesting in front of us, right?

166
00:14:20,302 --> 00:14:26,849
And that's a point where we can also recognize that all this stuff is arising whether we want it to or not.

167
00:14:27,349 --> 00:14:30,893
And that again points to this business of control.

168
00:14:30,952 --> 00:14:40,662
And something you can do when you're in that position of the observer is reflect what's it like being just the observer.

169
00:14:41,102 --> 00:14:45,346
Because in the observer, there's no emotions, there's no thoughts, and there's no sensations.

170
00:14:45,985 --> 00:15:14,996
keep working on that right because uh that's that's that identity is uh you know is a is a fraction of um the experience of nirvana right we'll come to that another time so uh we're into this objectivization and uh i want to give you um another image that you can work with and that's this myth of of uh narcissus

171
00:15:15,297 --> 00:15:43,227
now remember Narcissus looks into the pool this very beautiful young man and he falls in love with himself with the image and he goes to embrace himself and of course falls in and drowns now in mythology water is creation normally it's often used for an image for creation and Narcissus is sitting on the bank

172
00:15:43,342 --> 00:15:49,317
And he looks onto the surface of the water, into the water, and he catches his own image.

173
00:15:49,697 --> 00:15:50,681
Okay?

174
00:15:50,701 --> 00:15:57,417
Now, that's exactly what's happening with this satipanya, with this intuitive awareness, with the Buddha within.

175
00:15:58,197 --> 00:16:00,102
It looks into...

176
00:16:00,269 --> 00:16:06,216
the mind, the heart-mind complex, the body-heart-mind complex, the psycho-physical organism.

177
00:16:06,937 --> 00:16:14,869
And what it sees is that surface consciousness upon which everything is rising, and it captures its own image.

178
00:16:15,269 --> 00:16:22,158
And that's the sense of the observer, the feeler, the experiencer, the sense of presence.

179
00:16:22,678 --> 00:16:31,971
In other words, that mirror, that scheme, that surface is mirroring back to the awareness, its own presence.

180
00:16:33,032 --> 00:16:45,648
Now, what happens is, of course, you get lost, you dive into, you go into the world that the mind is creating on that very same surface.

181
00:16:46,649 --> 00:16:49,692
And that's what we're experiencing.

182
00:16:49,732 --> 00:16:51,235
That's the...

183
00:16:51,855 --> 00:17:19,837
bubble of consciousness that is our world and it's specific it's just our world i i can't know your world i've got some idea of it but i can't experience your world as your world and so everything that i experience is very personal to me it's very subjective but i'm actually creating it when i say i i mean of course the body the heart mind

184
00:17:20,459 --> 00:17:24,084
The psychophysical organism is creating the information.

185
00:17:25,045 --> 00:17:31,653
And what's happening is that this intuitive awareness is drowning in it.

186
00:17:31,914 --> 00:17:33,056
That's the delusion.

187
00:17:33,135 --> 00:17:37,221
It thinks that this is where true happiness is to be found.

188
00:17:37,281 --> 00:17:40,527
And of course, it fails.

189
00:17:42,048 --> 00:17:45,133
Our practice is to objectify all that, to see it.

190
00:17:45,993 --> 00:17:49,638
Right there in front of our inner eye, you could say,

191
00:17:49,872 --> 00:17:50,913
manifesting.

192
00:17:51,773 --> 00:17:56,999
And in so doing, of course, we're pulling out this quality of intuitive awareness.

193
00:17:57,980 --> 00:18:02,424
Now, that's as far as we can go by our own practice and act of will.

194
00:18:02,545 --> 00:18:04,807
We can determine that, right?

195
00:18:04,847 --> 00:18:10,513
We can just push things away from us inwardly and make them an object.

196
00:18:11,213 --> 00:18:14,698
But you can't push that sense of the observer away.

197
00:18:15,303 --> 00:18:18,627
That just creates another self trying to get rid of the observer.

198
00:18:19,450 --> 00:18:23,957
So in a sense, you've got to either, you can do two things.

199
00:18:24,698 --> 00:18:29,025
You can either, as it were, from that position, just glance back.

200
00:18:30,748 --> 00:18:36,938
And what I mean by glancing back is the question, what's inside this observer?

201
00:18:38,601 --> 00:18:39,942
What's inside it, right?

202
00:18:40,192 --> 00:18:43,537
We know what's inside the body, the feelings, the sensations.

203
00:18:43,997 --> 00:18:46,900
We know what's inside the heart, the emotions, the moods.

204
00:18:47,381 --> 00:18:50,144
And we know what's inside the mind, thoughts, images.

205
00:18:50,523 --> 00:18:52,405
What's inside the observer?

206
00:18:55,028 --> 00:19:01,394
And that's one way of sort of indicating that it's something which is of a completely different order.

207
00:19:01,615 --> 00:19:05,038
It doesn't belong to this psychophysical organism.

208
00:19:05,920 --> 00:19:08,563
And the next thing is that you can...

209
00:19:09,623 --> 00:19:34,752
turn your attention towards the sense of self of that observer right the sense of somebody observing and just keep your eye there just wondering where is that being manufactured okay and after that really uh you just have to uh wait until the the insight arises

210
00:19:34,852 --> 00:19:40,417
And this is one way of investigating this whole teaching around not-self.

211
00:19:40,919 --> 00:19:44,102
So remember, the Buddha is not saying there's no self.

212
00:19:44,321 --> 00:19:49,067
He's saying that any self is manufactured.

213
00:19:49,087 --> 00:19:51,009
It's being constructed.

214
00:19:52,171 --> 00:19:57,537
And our whole purpose is to deconstruct that.

215
00:19:59,098 --> 00:20:02,321
So remember, this is just one avenue of investigation.

216
00:20:02,823 --> 00:20:04,825
So the other two avenues which will

217
00:20:04,990 --> 00:20:17,930
hopefully come to later because now we've got another three weeks of lockdown, would be understanding desire and looking more deeply at impermanence.

218
00:20:18,289 --> 00:20:18,570
Okay.

219
00:20:19,291 --> 00:20:32,432
So just to recap there, when you've got your sitting posture correct and you're calm, you can do it with the breath.

220
00:20:32,884 --> 00:20:38,589
or with a very loud sensation, the knee.

221
00:20:39,210 --> 00:20:45,615
It's often actually better with something louder and to actually go into it and deconstruct it.

222
00:20:46,396 --> 00:20:55,064
In the discourse on how to establish this awareness, the Buddha actually encourages us to do that.

223
00:20:55,084 --> 00:21:02,250
He says to feel feelings in feelings, to experience mental states in mental states.

224
00:21:02,602 --> 00:21:07,386
He's asking us to go into it and to deconstruct it.

225
00:21:08,126 --> 00:21:13,132
And my own teacher, one of my own teachers, Sayuru Pandita, used to talk about plunging it.

226
00:21:13,512 --> 00:21:23,241
You have to plunge, plunge into your experience and deconstruct it, by which we mean find out what its constituents are.

227
00:21:23,541 --> 00:21:25,124
Okay.

228
00:21:25,144 --> 00:21:31,630
And the second thing is to recognize that when we've discovered that position of the observer, this observation post,

229
00:21:32,385 --> 00:21:36,189
to see that everything's happening of its own accord.

230
00:21:36,269 --> 00:21:42,013
It's happening beyond our commanding.

231
00:21:42,434 --> 00:21:46,838
It's not within our personal power when we've taken that position.

232
00:21:47,479 --> 00:21:50,801
So sensations arise, feelings arise, et cetera, et cetera.

233
00:21:51,682 --> 00:22:02,291
And the third thing is, of course, to recognize that everything we're looking at is an object, not me, not me, not mine,

234
00:22:02,643 --> 00:22:03,544
and not a self.

235
00:22:06,929 --> 00:22:13,257
So I hope that's helpful, and you might have a go at it this evening's meditation.

236
00:22:14,417 --> 00:22:17,201
So it's just a way of sort of practicing.

237
00:22:17,663 --> 00:22:31,079
And then, of course, when we get into that steady position of just observing, just feeling, just experiencing, just that, then, of course, you let go of all that,

238
00:22:31,448 --> 00:22:41,383
And have this confidence, this real inner confidence, trust that this intuitive awareness can work it out for itself.

239
00:22:41,823 --> 00:22:43,184
It doesn't need us at all.

240
00:22:43,546 --> 00:22:48,613
It doesn't need this person talking and guiding it.

241
00:22:50,155 --> 00:22:51,356
And just watch.

242
00:22:51,458 --> 00:22:51,998
That's enough.

243
00:22:52,259 --> 00:22:56,545
Whatever draws the attention within that field of awareness, that's it.

244
00:22:57,740 --> 00:22:58,321
Very good.

245
00:22:58,482 --> 00:23:04,383
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance that it's not caused even greater confusion.

246
00:23:05,105 --> 00:23:09,119
So I think it's time that we can begin our meditation again.

247
00:23:09,480 --> 00:23:09,942
Very good.

248
00:23:32,282 --> 00:23:36,585
You see, I've kind of forgotten this little gadget again.

